Gateway — Kong implementation change log

Source: Archive/Development/Backend/ChangeRequest/Request-001. Design constraints: ARCHITECTURE.md §6 (external API surface), §7 (gateway security), §11 (build layout, reserves gateway/kong.decl.yaml). No existing service code touched (identity-service/catalog-service/order-service/notification-service are out of scope — separate work item). No new Gradle module, library, or dependency added to build.gradle.kts/gradle/libs.versions.toml — Kong is a standalone container, not a JVM dependency, so there's nothing to add to the version catalog.

New files:

- `gateway/kong.decl.yaml` — Kong's DB-less declarative config (`_format_version: "3.0"`), the path ARCHITECTURE.md §11 already reserved for it. Contains 4 `services` (identity/catalog/order/notification-service, one URL each matching that service's `application.yml` port), 17 `routes` covering every method+path extracted from Phase-1 through Phase-7, a route-scoped `jwt` plugin on every route except `POST /api/auth/register` and `POST /api/auth/login`, a global `cors` plugin, a global `rate-limiting` plugin (redis policy) with a stricter route-level override on the login route, and one `consumer` (`identity-service`) holding the JWT credential Kong verifies tokens against.

  - **[Decision] Route-level `jwt` plugin (explicit per-route opt-in via YAML anchor), not a global plugin with an anonymous-consumer bypass.** ARCHITECTURE.md §7 requires register/login to be reachable without a token. Kong has no native "apply this global plugin to all routes except these two" primitive; the two ways to get the excluded behavior are (a) attach `jwt` per-route and simply omit it on the two exempt routes, or (b) attach it globally and configure an anonymous-consumer fallback that register/login's route additionally overrides to bypass. (a) was chosen: every route's protection status is visible at the route definition itself in a config-file diff, with no second layer of anonymous-consumer indirection to cross-reference. The YAML anchor (`&jwt-verify`/`*jwt-verify`) keeps this DRY without needing a Kong-specific mechanism — pure YAML, resolved before Kong ever parses the document.

  - **[Decision] `{id}` path segments matched as UUID-shaped regexes (`[0-9a-fA-F]{8}-...`), not a generic `[^/]+` wildcard.** The obvious wildcard approach needed a negative-lookahead regex to keep `/api/users/{id}` from also matching `/api/users/me` — Kong 3.x's router doesn't support regex look-around (see Archive/Issues/Gateway0). Phase-1's own convention fixes every ID as a UUID string, so a UUID pattern both resolves the collision and is a more precise match than a wildcard would have been anyway.

  - **[Decision] `GET /api/products` and `GET /api/products/{id}` have no `jwt` plugin.** Phase-3 (CAT-006) states these are public/anonymous browsing endpoints — the only two endpoints across all 18 extracted method+path pairs that don't require a token, besides register/login.

  - **[Decision] Every route also accepts `OPTIONS`, and the `jwt` plugin sets `run_on_preflight: false`.** Without `OPTIONS` in a route's declared methods, Kong's router won't match a browser's CORS preflight request at all (404, not a CORS response) — found by actually issuing a preflight request against the running container, see Archive/Issues/Gateway0. Once `OPTIONS` was added, JWT-protected routes then demanded a token on the preflight itself (the plugin's true default), which no browser ever sends on a preflight; `run_on_preflight: false` turns that off without weakening verification on the real request.

  - **[Decision] `rate-limiting` global default of 60/minute, login route override of 5/minute, `policy: redis`.** BUSINESS_RULES.md and ARCHITECTURE.md don't specify numeric thresholds — ARCHITECTURE.md §7 only says login should be tighter, to slow credential-stuffing. These two numbers are this implementation's judgment call, not a business requirement; a real deployment should revisit them against actual traffic. `policy: redis` (not `local`) is not a judgment call — ARCHITECTURE.md §7 states it explicitly, reusing the same Redis instance already required for caching, on a separate logical DB index (`database: 1`) from app-level caching (`database: 0`, per ARCHITECTURE.md §9) to avoid key collisions.

  - **[Decision] `cors.origins` is a single placeholder, `http://localhost:5173`.** ARCHITECTURE.md §7 requires an explicit allow-list (never `*`), but no real frontend origin exists yet in this repo. Rather than invent a plausible-looking production domain, the config uses an unambiguous local-dev placeholder, commented as needing replacement before any real deployment.

  - **[Decision] The consumer's `rsa_public_key` field is a placeholder token (`__IDENTITY_DEV_PUBLIC_KEY__`), substituted at container start, not committed as literal PEM text.** `gateway/keys/identity-dev-public-key.pem` is a shared-file contract with the parallel identity-service RS256 login work, which had not landed as of this change. Kong's own declarative-config loader has no "read this file path" field type (verified against Kong 3.x's docs and empirically via `kong config parse`), so a literal file-path reference inside `kong.decl.yaml` was never going to work on its own — see `gateway/docker-entrypoint.sh` below for how the substitution actually happens. Fabricating a real-looking key just to make the container start was explicitly ruled out by Request-001.

- `gateway/docker-entrypoint.sh` — a small render step that runs before Kong starts: fails fast with a clear error if `gateway/keys/identity-dev-public-key.pem` is missing (refusing to start, rather than starting with a fabricated key), otherwise substitutes that file's contents for the placeholder above and delegates to the official `kong:3.x` image's own `/docker-entrypoint.sh kong docker-start` (chaining into it, not replacing it — `kong docker-start` is not a real subcommand of the `kong` CLI on its own, see Archive/Issues/Gateway0).

- `gateway/keys/.gitkeep` — keeps the directory present in the repo (and thus mountable by docker-compose) before the real public key exists. No key material is committed.

- `Archive/Development/Backend/Implementation/Gateway`, `Archive/Development/Backend/ChangeLog/Gateway` (this file), `Archive/Issues/Gateway0` — the three deliverables Request-001 asked for.

Changes to existing files:

- `docker-compose.yml` — added one new service, `kong` (container name `kotlincrud-kong`, matching this file's existing `kotlincrud-` prefix convention).

  - **[Decision] Image pinned to `kong:3.9.3`, not the `3.15.0` figure ARCHITECTURE.md §6 cites as "most recent release found in this session."** Checked directly against Docker Hub's registry API at implementation time (`registry.hub.docker.com/v2/repositories/library/kong/tags`): the newest published tag under the official `library/kong` repository is `3.9.3` (last updated 2026-07-02); no `3.15.x` tag exists there. ARCHITECTURE.md's figure may refer to Kong's overall/enterprise release numbering rather than what's actually published as a pullable OSS Docker image — flagging the discrepancy here rather than either blindly trusting the architecture doc or silently picking a different, unverified number. `3.9.3` is a real, verified, pinned tag, consistent with how every other image in this file is pinned to a specific version.

  - **[Decision] Only port 8000 (HTTP proxy) is published to the host; 8001 (admin API) is not, despite being Kong's default listen port inside the container.** ARCHITECTURE.md §7 states the network boundary in one sentence: "only Kong is reachable from outside." The admin API is Kong's control plane — in DB-less mode it can't be used to change routing (that's a redeploy-the-YAML operation), but it can still read back the entire config, including the JWT consumer's public key, whether a rate limit is currently tripped, and every route defined, which is more surface area than a security-conscious local setup needs exposed to the host. It's left reachable inside the Docker network (for the `kong health` healthcheck, which runs inside the container's own namespace regardless of what's published) — just not published.

  - **[Decision] No 8443/TLS.** ARCHITECTURE.md §7 explicitly defers real TLS/ACME as out of scope and allows a self-signed cert for local dev as an honestly-documented simplification. This implementation goes one step further and skips the self-signed cert too, serving plain HTTP on 8000 for local dev — building a self-signed TLS setup that nobody asked for and that isn't wired to anything real would be effort spent to *look* more secure without being more secure. Flagged plainly as a gap in the implementation guide, not silently glossed over.

  - No other service's `ports:` mapping was touched. ARCHITECTURE.md §7 implies that, in a fully hardened setup, only Kong would ultimately be host-published — postgres/mongodb/rabbitmq/redis/jaeger/prometheus/grafana all currently publish host ports too. Changing that is explicitly out of scope for this change (bigger blast radius, affects every other developer's local workflow, e.g. connecting a local DB client to postgres:5432) — noted as a deferred hardening item in the implementation guide, not silently done here.

  - `depends_on: [redis]` (plain list, matching this file's existing style for `prometheus`/`grafana` rather than introducing a `condition: service_healthy` gate this file doesn't otherwise use). Not a strict requirement: the `rate-limiting` plugin's `fault_tolerant: true` means Kong still proxies requests even if Redis isn't reachable yet at startup.
